[{"data":1,"prerenderedAt":461},["ShallowReactive",2],{"header-locale:\u002Fen\u002Fnodejs\u002F2021\u002F10\u002F27\u002Fnpm-ci-vs-npm-install-differences\u002F":3,"page:\u002Fen\u002Fnodejs\u002F2021\u002F10\u002F27\u002Fnpm-ci-vs-npm-install-differences\u002F":4,"alt:\u002Fen\u002Fnodejs\u002F2021\u002F10\u002F27\u002Fnpm-ci-vs-npm-install-differences\u002F":3,"prev-next:\u002Fen\u002Fnodejs\u002F2021\u002F10\u002F27\u002Fnpm-ci-vs-npm-install-differences\u002F":436,"related:\u002Fen\u002Fnodejs\u002F2021\u002F10\u002F27\u002Fnpm-ci-vs-npm-install-differences\u002F":445},"\u002Fnodejs\u002F20211027\u002F1827968017\u002F",{"id":5,"title":6,"abbrlink":7,"altUrl":3,"body":8,"category":417,"date":418,"description":419,"extension":420,"lang":421,"meta":422,"navigation":423,"path":424,"readingMinutes":425,"seo":426,"standalone":427,"stem":428,"tags":429,"tldr":432,"updated":433,"url":434,"__hash__":435},"content\u002Fen\u002FNodejs\u002Fnpm-ci-vs-npm-install-differences.md","npm ci vs npm install: What's the Difference?","7176819812",{"type":9,"value":10,"toc":408},"minimark",[11,37,42,51,55,65,88,97,101,107,117,123,133,142,154,166,173,183,201,216,222,228,240,279,290,295,300,305,310,321,325,345,348,364,373,382,386],[12,13,14],"blockquote",{},[15,16,17,21,25,26,29,30,25,33,36],"p",{},[18,19,20],"strong",{},"Note",[22,23,24],"code",{},"npm ci"," restores from ",[22,27,28],{},"package-lock.json"," with versions locked — good for CI\u002FCD and team restores. ",[22,31,32],{},"npm install",[22,34,35],{},"package.json"," and can quietly bump versions — good for adding or updating dependencies during dev.",[38,39,41],"h2",{"id":40},"intro","Intro",[15,43,44,45,47,48,50],{},"Most of us are used to running ",[22,46,32],{}," to restore a project, but since npm 5.7.1 a lot of folks recommend ",[22,49,24],{}," instead. Let's go through why.",[38,52,54],{"id":53},"what-is-npm-ci","What is npm ci?",[15,56,57,58,60,61,64],{},"The \"ci\" in ",[22,59,24],{}," stands for ",[18,62,63],{},"Continuous Integration",". It was introduced in npm 5.7.1, so if your npm is older than that, you can't use this command.",[15,66,67,68,70,71,74,75,77,78,80,81,83,84,87],{},"It's similar to ",[22,69,32],{}," (and ",[22,72,73],{},"npm i","). Officially ",[22,76,24],{}," is supposed to install faster than ",[22,79,32],{},", but in my own tests ",[22,82,32],{}," was actually faster. From what I've read in discussions, that's usually because ",[22,85,86],{},"node_modules"," is cached.",[15,89,90,91,93,94,96],{},"So what's the actual difference between ",[22,92,24],{}," and ",[22,95,32],{},"? Let's keep going.",[38,98,100],{"id":99},"npm-install-vs-npm-ci","npm install vs npm ci",[15,102,103,104,106],{},"First, ",[22,105,32],{},". You'd typically use it in two situations:",[108,109,110,114],"ul",{},[111,112,113],"li",{},"Installing a specific package",[111,115,116],{},"Restoring a project",[15,118,119,120,122],{},"When ",[22,121,32],{}," finishes, you usually see two things appear:",[108,124,125,129],{},[111,126,127],{},[22,128,86],{},[111,130,131],{},[22,132,28],{},[15,134,135,136,138,139,141],{},"We can skip ",[22,137,86],{}," — that's just where packages live. The interesting one is ",[22,140,28],{},".",[15,143,144,146,147,149,150,153],{},[22,145,28],{}," looks a bit like the ",[22,148,35],{}," that ",[22,151,152],{},"npm init"," generates, except it records dependency versions in painful detail. It was introduced in npm 5, and its job is to lock the exact dependency versions an install produced.",[15,155,156,157,93,159,161,162,165],{},"If you actually open ",[22,158,35],{},[22,160,28],{}," side by side, you'll see how much more detailed the lock file is. Here's ",[22,163,164],{},"axios"," as an example:",[15,167,168],{},[169,170],"img",{"alt":171,"src":172},"package-lock.json vs package.json","https:\u002F\u002Fi.imgur.com\u002FAZcXwUx.png",[15,174,175,176,178,179,182],{},"It even records what ",[22,177,164],{}," depends on (like ",[22,180,181],{},"follow-redirects",").",[15,184,185,186,188,189,198,199,141],{},"So why am I making a big deal of ",[22,187,28],{},"? Because ",[18,190,191,25,193,195,196],{},[22,192,24],{},[22,194,28],{},", not from ",[22,197,35],{}," — that's the key difference from ",[22,200,32],{},[15,202,203,204,206,207,209,210,212,213,215],{},"What's the benefit of restoring with ",[22,205,24],{},"? The short version is: ",[22,208,24],{}," is built for CI\u002FCD and test environments. But why is it recommended for restoring dev environments too? You've probably hit this — when you take over a project and run ",[22,211,32],{},", npm quietly updates some things, and ",[22,214,28],{}," ends up modified for no obvious reason. If you've got version control turned on, it shows up like this:",[15,217,218],{},[169,219],{"alt":220,"src":221},"Files quietly updated","https:\u002F\u002Fi.imgur.com\u002FzQr0rnn.png",[15,223,224,225,227],{},"(Side note: yes, you should commit ",[22,226,28],{}," to version control.)",[15,229,230,231,233,234,236,237,239],{},"These silent updates can lead to package version incompatibilities and other \"why is this broken?\" debugging sessions. That's where ",[22,232,24],{}," helps — since it installs from ",[22,235,28],{},", the versions are exactly what the lock file says, no surprise updates. A few things to be aware of when using ",[22,238,24],{},":",[108,241,242,252,257,263,271],{},[111,243,244,245,247,248,251],{},"You must have a ",[22,246,28],{}," or ",[22,249,250],{},"npm-shrinkwrap.json"," (another lockfile, less common).",[111,253,254,256],{},[22,255,24],{}," can only restore the entire dependency tree at once — you can't install one package with it (which you probably wouldn't want anyway).",[111,258,259,260,262],{},"If ",[22,261,86],{}," already exists, it deletes the folder first and then installs.",[111,264,265,266,268,269,141],{},"If a dependency error occurs during install, ",[22,267,24],{}," exits instead of touching ",[22,270,35],{},[111,272,273,275,276,278],{},[22,274,24],{}," never modifies ",[22,277,35],{},", so versions stay locked.",[15,280,281,283,284,289],{},[22,282,24],{}," sounds great for restores. The official line is that ",[18,285,286,287],{},"it's faster than ",[22,288,32],{},", and here's a comparison:",[15,291,292,294],{},[22,293,32],{}," took 16 seconds:",[15,296,297],{},[169,298],{"alt":32,"src":299},"https:\u002F\u002Fi.imgur.com\u002FJRRkYB7.png",[15,301,302,304],{},[22,303,24],{}," took 14 seconds:",[15,306,307],{},[169,308],{"alt":24,"src":309},"https:\u002F\u002Fi.imgur.com\u002FPhYUyf7.png",[15,311,312,313,320],{},"Honestly, I think they're basically the same — see the ",[314,315,319],"a",{"href":316,"rel":317},"https:\u002F\u002Fdocs.npmjs.com\u002Fcli\u002Fv6\u002Fcommands\u002Fnpm-ci",[318],"nofollow","official docs"," for more on this.",[38,322,324],{"id":323},"so-which-should-i-use-npm-install-or-npm-ci","So which should I use — npm install or npm ci?",[15,326,327,328,332,333,335,336,338,339,341,342,344],{},"Both have their place. When you want to restore ",[329,330,331],"em",{},"and"," update packages, use ",[22,334,32],{},". When you want exact versions and don't want to touch ",[22,337,28],{},", use ",[22,340,24],{},". And for CI\u002FCD, ",[22,343,24],{}," is the better, more reliable choice.",[15,346,347],{},"There's a lot of reading on this if you want to go deeper:",[108,349,350,357],{},[111,351,352],{},[314,353,356],{"href":354,"rel":355},"https:\u002F\u002Fbetterprogramming.pub\u002Fnpm-ci-vs-npm-install-which-should-you-use-in-your-node-js-projects-51e07cb71e26",[318],"npm ci vs. npm install — Which Should You Use in Your Node.js Projects?",[111,358,359],{},[314,360,363],{"href":361,"rel":362},"https:\u002F\u002Fstackoverflow.com\u002Fquestions\u002F52499617\u002Fwhat-is-the-difference-between-npm-install-and-npm-ci",[318],"What is the difference between \"npm install\" and \"npm ci\"?",[15,365,366,367,369,370,372],{},"Some folks even argue you should always use ",[22,368,24],{}," instead of ",[22,371,32],{}," for restores:",[108,374,375],{},[111,376,377],{},[314,378,381],{"href":379,"rel":380},"https:\u002F\u002Fstackoverflow.com\u002Fquestions\u002F53469032\u002Fusing-npm-ci-instead-of-npm-install-for-deterministic-project-setup",[318],"Using \"npm ci\" instead of \"npm install\" for deterministic project setup",[38,383,385],{"id":384},"references","References",[108,387,388,393,398,403],{},[111,389,390],{},[314,391,24],{"href":316,"rel":392},[318],[111,394,395],{},[314,396,356],{"href":354,"rel":397},[318],[111,399,400],{},[314,401,363],{"href":361,"rel":402},[318],[111,404,405],{},[314,406,381],{"href":379,"rel":407},[318],{"title":409,"searchDepth":410,"depth":410,"links":411},"",2,[412,413,414,415,416],{"id":40,"depth":410,"text":41},{"id":53,"depth":410,"text":54},{"id":99,"depth":410,"text":100},{"id":323,"depth":410,"text":324},{"id":384,"depth":410,"text":385},"Nodejs","2021-10-27 21:24:14","Most of us are used to running `npm install` when restoring a project, but since npm 5.7.1 there's been a recommendation to use `npm ci` instead. This post walks through why, and when each one is the right call.","md","en",{},true,"\u002Fen\u002Fnodejs\u002Fnpm-ci-vs-npm-install-differences","4",{"title":6,"description":419},false,"en\u002FNodejs\u002Fnpm-ci-vs-npm-install-differences",[430,431],"npm","Node.js",null,"2026-05-12 09:00:00","\u002Fen\u002Fnodejs\u002F2021\u002F10\u002F27\u002Fnpm-ci-vs-npm-install-differences\u002F","a5KhnsADCdgR7Oygcm4nCf7UTqC_mzkCgYmdJ0ekh4o",{"newer":437,"older":441},{"url":438,"title":439,"date":440},"\u002Fen\u002Fjavascript\u002F2021\u002F10\u002F29\u002Fforeach-async-await-problem\u002F","Why Does async\u002Fawait Quietly Break Inside forEach? (And How to Fix It)","2021-10-29 21:38:47",{"url":442,"title":443,"date":444},"\u002Fen\u002Fjavascript\u002F2021\u002F10\u002F24\u002Fjavascript-core-68-es6-arrow-functions-exercise\u002F","JavaScript Core Concepts (68) - ES6 Arrow Functions: Chapter Exercise","2021-10-24 16:57:45",[446,451,456],{"url":447,"title":448,"date":449,"readingMinutes":450},"\u002Fen\u002Fnodejs\u002F2026\u002F01\u002F13\u002Frun-multiple-commands-with-concurrently\u002F","Tired of Opening Multiple Terminals to Run Commands? Use Concurrently","2026-01-13 09:45:28","2",{"url":452,"title":453,"date":454,"readingMinutes":455},"\u002Fen\u002Fnodejs\u002F2025\u002F03\u002F13\u002Fhexschool-ecommerce-api-complete-tutorial\u002F","Hexschool Capstone Class Study Group: Complete E-commerce API Tutorial","2025-03-13 09:13:26","9",{"url":457,"title":458,"date":459,"readingMinutes":460},"\u002Fen\u002Fnodejs\u002F2024\u002F12\u002F25\u002Fpm2-process-manager-not-pm25\u002F","PM2 Is Process Manager, Not PM2.5","2024-12-25 10:31:33","5",1784012782775]